ce:section.ce:para:
In the next step, we evaluate the photocatalytic activity of LaFeO3 nanostructures under UV light. Fig. 13
                     a, b shows the degradation efficiency for erythrosine as organic pollution under UV irradiation in 90 min. In this case, UV power was 400 W and organic pollution concentration was 10 ppm. As the red curve shows, the sample prepared without a capping agent degrades 65% of erythrosine in 90 min. By changing the photocatalyst to sample 11, degradation efficiency boost to 79% (green curve). Changing capping agent to starch increased degradation yield to 93.5% (purple curve). Finally using sample 13 as catalyst leads to degrades 96% of erythrosine (blue curve). Fig. 13c, d shows the photocatalytic activity of samples without and with different capping agents when organic pollution was eriochrome black T. Based on the results, degradation efficiency was 68% when sample without capping agent was used as a catalyst (black curve). By using rice as a capping agent, 70% of eriochrome black T was degraded (red curve). As the green curve shows, degradation efficiency increased to 79% when starch was used as a capping agent. Based on data presented in the blue curve, 84% of eriochrome black T degraded when corn was used as a capping agent. According to these results, a sample prepared by using starch shows very high photocatalytic activity under UV light. This could happen because it containing F2O3. As the XRD result shows, F2O3 was formed as an impurity when starch was used as a capping agent. F2O3 has wide bandgap so it could be a good photocatalyst under UV light and boos the efficiency. This impurity act as co-absorbent under UV light and boost efficiency by 43% (Scheme 1
                     ).
